docs.abstract: Boone, a former cultural commissioner for Chicago, will take the helm after tumult over racial justice at the foundation, one of the country’s wealthiest literary organizations.
docs.snippet: Boone, a former cultural commissioner for Chicago, will take the helm after tumult over racial justice at the foundation, one of the country’s wealthiest literary organizations.
docs.lead_paragraph: Michelle T. Boone, a former commissioner of cultural affairs for the City of Chicago, has been named president of the Poetry Foundation, nearly a year after the previous president resigned amid an intense outcry over the Chicago-based organization’s perceived lack of commitment to social justice.

headline.main: Michelle T. Boone Named President of Poetry Foundation
headline.print_headline: A New Voice at the Helm of the Poetry Foundation

docs.abstract: A return to in-person awards meant a return to fashion form for many celebrities. Have we learned nothing from the past year?
docs.snippet: A return to in-person awards meant a return to fashion form for many celebrities. Have we learned nothing from the past year?
docs.lead_paragraph: The 93rd annual Academy Awards were a night of historic firsts: first woman of color to win the directing Oscar; first Black women to win the makeup and hairstyling Oscar; oldest woman ever to win an Oscar; first Korean actor to win an Oscar. But in at least one area it was more like same-old, same-old: the red carpet.

headline.main: On the Oscars Red Carpet: A Lot of Style, Little Substance
headline.print_headline: On a Glittery Red Carpet, a Year Changes Little

docs.abstract: The Pasquotank County Sheriff’s Office said that a deputy who was executing a search warrant and an arrest warrant fatally shot Andrew Brown Jr. in Elizabeth City. Residents gathered at the scene to demand answers.
docs.snippet: The Pasquotank County Sheriff’s Office said that a deputy who was executing a search warrant and an arrest warrant fatally shot Andrew Brown Jr. in Elizabeth City. Residents gathered at the scene to demand answers.
docs.lead_paragraph: A sheriff’s deputy shot and killed a Black man on Wednesday morning in Elizabeth City, N.C., while executing a search warrant and an arrest warrant on drug charges, the authorities said.

headline.main: Sheriff’s Deputy Kills Black Man in North Carolina

byline.original: By Christina Morales and Michael Levenson

docs.abstract: If the industry won’t change on principle, it can at least change for the money. Reform would enrich people of color, and everyone else.
docs.snippet: If the industry won’t change on principle, it can at least change for the money. Reform would enrich people of color, and everyone else.
docs.lead_paragraph: Days after a Minneapolis police officer, Derek Chauvin, suffocated George Floyd and the video went viral, I watched my social media feed fill with blackout tiles and corporate publicity statements. They poured in from every industry, proclaiming solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement. Hollywood — where I have worked for almost two decades — was no exception.

headline.main: Hollywood’s Anti-Black Bias Costs It $10 Billion a Year
headline.print_headline: Hollywood Bias Comes at a Hefty Price

docs.abstract: Clayton County Sheriff Victor Hill is accused of ordering detainees to be strapped down for hours at a time as punishment, federal prosecutors said.
docs.snippet: Clayton County Sheriff Victor Hill is accused of ordering detainees to be strapped down for hours at a time as punishment, federal prosecutors said.
docs.lead_paragraph: An Atlanta-area sheriff with a history of legal troubles faces federal civil rights charges for ordering several detainees to be strapped to restraint chairs for hours at a time even though they posed no danger to deputies, prosecutors said.

headline.main: Georgia Sheriff Faces Civil Rights Charges Over Use of Restraint Chairs

docs.abstract: Protesters have rallied across cities in England and Wales to denounce new legislation that would give the police more powers to dislodge demonstrators at gatherings.
docs.snippet: Protesters have rallied across cities in England and Wales to denounce new legislation that would give the police more powers to dislodge demonstrators at gatherings.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Thousands of people protested Saturday in several cities across England and Wales against a sweeping crime and policing bill, with some in London clashing with the police in scenes that may further fuel a raging national debate over law enforcement tactics in Britain.

headline.main: Thousands Protest Against Policing Bill in Britain, With Clashes in London

docs.abstract: A jury finds Derek Chauvin guilty.
docs.snippet: A jury finds Derek Chauvin guilty.
docs.lead_paragraph: Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer, was found guilty yesterday on all three charges he faced in the death last year of George Floyd, capping one of the most-watched trials in the U.S. in recent memory. Follow live reactions.

docs.abstract: The boycott, set to begin on Friday, is the most direct effort yet by a sport to pressure social media companies like Twitter, Instagram and Facebook to take action against abuse.
docs.snippet: The boycott, set to begin on Friday, is the most direct effort yet by a sport to pressure social media companies like Twitter, Instagram and Facebook to take action against abuse.
docs.lead_paragraph: English soccer will conduct a social media blackout this weekend to protest “the ongoing and sustained discriminatory abuse received online by players and many others connected to football.”

headline.main: English Soccer Will Boycott Social Media to Protest Online Abuse
headline.print_headline: English Soccer Is Set to Boycott Social Media Over Online Abuse
